history.content:
EDIT: Sorry, I think we are having a hard time understanding the question. 

Physics 7B is an alternative to 16A, but you need to be careful with overlap. 

If you took Physics 7B for a major or a minor then you can't use it for 16A.

If it was for a breadth it's okay to overlap.
I think the sentence you're pointing to may have been directed at students who are double majors/minors who may have needed physics for their second major. 
If this did not answer your question, please contact your major adviser directly.

Per the announcement for LSCS seniors graduating between Fall 2016 and Fall 2017, you cannot use a course from the provided list to fulfill two requirements. If you have taken Physics 7B for one of your breadth requirements, you may not use it to also satisfy the EE16A requirement.

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1HQPOTGSqF4EMAsU9eocvrfcytDms1al37eJ9nsTdgds/edit?pref=2&pli=1

It's listed in the Course List but above the course list, it says " If you have taken Math 54 and Physics 7B, 16B may be the most natural alternative course for you to take". But if physics 7b is already an alternative, why would you need to take 16B as the "alternate course"
history.subject: Is Physics 7B an alternative to EE16A?
